<h3><strong>1. Antiquity and Early Alchemy</strong></h3>
Tungsten's story begins in antiquity, where early civilizations had encounters with minerals containing tungsten without realizing its unique properties. The mineral wolframite, one of the primary sources of tungsten, was often confused with other ores due to its similar appearance, hindering its recognition as a distinct element.

&nbsp;
<h3><strong>2. Scheelite's Discovery</strong></h3>
The true understanding of tungsten's distinct characteristics came in the 18th century with the discovery of scheelite, another tungsten-containing mineral. Swedish chemist Carl Wilhelm Scheele played a pivotal role in isolating tungstic acid from scheelite in 1781. However, the element's isolation remained elusive, and its true nature remained obscured.

&nbsp;
<h3><strong>3. Identification and Naming</strong></h3>
The next chapter in tungsten's history unfolded in 1783 when the element was identified by Spanish chemists Juan Jose and Fausto Elhuyar. They successfully isolated tungsten from wolframite, marking the first time tungsten stood alone as a distinct element. The Elhuyar brothers named the newfound element "wolfram," a term still used in some parts of the world. The name "tungsten" emerged later, derived from the Swedish words "tung sten," meaning "heavy stone."

&nbsp;
<h3><strong>4. The Challenge of Reduction</strong></h3>
Despite its recognition as a distinct element, the reduction of tungsten from its ores presented a formidable challenge to early chemists. Its extremely high melting point and resistance to reduction posed obstacles to obtaining the pure metal, delaying its widespread use in various applications.

&nbsp;
<h3><strong>5. Industrial Revolution and Tungsten Alloys</strong></h3>
