Rhenium's importance escalated during World War II, as its properties proved strategically significant. The alloying capabilities of Rhenium with tungsten created superalloys essential for high-temperature applications in jet engines and military equipment. The demand for these high-performance materials surged, highlighting Rhenium's role in advancing aerospace technology.

